{"cursor":"23955","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Jerome Ysroael Lettvin image = Lettvin_Faraday_cage.jpg image_size =\n| 266x214px alt = caption = Jerome Lettvin in Building 20 at MIT in 1952 [http://jerome.lettvin.info/lettvin/Jerome/JeromeYLettvinStori-\n| es.pdf \"Jerome Lettvin Stories\"], More Data, More Noise: A Celebration of the\n| 60th Birthday of Jerome Y. Lettvin, MIT, February 1980. birth_date =\n| birth_place = Chicago, Illinois, USA death_date = death_place = Hingham,\n| Massachusetts, USA residence = citizenship = nationality = American fields =\n| Psychiatry, Neuroscience, Philosophy, Electrical Engineering, Communications\n| Physiology, Mythopoetry workplaces = Rutgers (1988â2011) MIT\n| (1951â2011) Stazione Zoologica Manteno State Hospital\n| (1948â1951) University of Rochester (1947) alma_mater = University of\n| Illinois (B.S., M.D. 1943) doctoral_advisor = academic_advisors =\n| notable_students = Norman Geschwind Squire 1998, p. 229 known_for =\n| \"What the Frog's Eye Tells the Frog's Brain\" Leary-Lettvin debate\n| author_abbrev_bot = author_abbrev_zoo = influences = Norbert Wiener Warren\n| McCulloch Walter Pitts Derek Denny-Brown Santiago RamÃ³n y\n| Cajal Charles Scott Sherrington John Zachary Young awards = signature =  signature_alt = footnotes =\n| spouse = Maggie (1947â)\n}}\n\n'Jerome Ysroael Lettvin' (February 23, 1920 â April 23, 2011) was an American\ncognitive scientist and professor Emeritus of Electrical and Bioengineering and\nCommunications Physiology at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). He\nis best known as the author of the 1959 paper, \"What the frog's eye tells the\nfrog's brain\", Lettvin, J.Y; Maturana, H.R.; McCulloch, W.S.; Pitts, W.H.,\n[http://jerome.lettvin.info/lettvin/Jerome/WhatTheFrogsEyeTellsTheFrogsBrain.pdf\nWhat the frog's eye tells the frog's brain], Proceedings of the IRE, Vol. 47,\nNo. 11, November 1959 one of the most cited papers in the Science Citation\nIndex. He wrote it along with Humberto Maturana, Warren McCulloch and Walter\nPitts and in the paper they gave special thanks and mention to the work of\nOliver Selfridge at MIT. \"We are particularly grateful to O. G. Selfridge,\nwhose experiments with mechanical recognizers of pattern helped drive us to this\nwork and whose criticism in part shaped its course.\" He carried out\nneurophysiological studies in the spinal cord, made the first demonstration of\n\"feature detectors\" in the visual system, and studied information processing in\nthe terminal branches of single axons. Around 1969, he originated the term\ngrandmother cell Gross, Charles G.,\n[http://www.as.wvu.edu/daly/439/readings/Gross%202002%20Grandmother%20Cell.pdf\nGenealogy of the \"Grandmother Cell\"], NEUROSCIENTIST 8(5):512â518, 2002. \nto illustrate the logical inconsistency of the concept.\n\nJerome Lettvin was popularly known as \"Jerry\", and was the author of many\npublished articles on subjects varying from neurology and physiology to\nphilosophy and politics. [http://jerome.lettvin.info Jerome\nLettvin page] Among his many activities at MIT, he served as one of the\nfirst directors of the Concourse Program, and, along with his wife Maggie,\nhouseparent of the Bexley dorm.\n","linknr":245,"url":"Jerome_Lettvin","recorded":1375088734,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Jerome_Lettvin&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Jerome_Lettvin&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org